## What Is a Yellow Cushion Cut Diamond

A yellow cushion cut diamond is a cushion-shaped diamond graded by GIA for body colour in the yellow range — at Fancy Light Yellow, Fancy Yellow, Fancy Intense Yellow, Fancy Deep Yellow, or Fancy Vivid Yellow on GIA's fancy colour scale. Unlike colourless cushion diamonds graded D through Z for absence of colour, fancy colour diamonds are graded on the intensity of colour saturation present in the stone. The cushion cut is the dominant shape in the natural yellow diamond market because its facet structure specifically advantages body colour visibility at every carat weight and grade tier.

The yellow cushion cut diamond market spans from entry-level Fancy Yellow at [$1,549 per carat](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-26394333?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) to Fancy Vivid Yellow collector stones exceeding $40,000 per carat — a range that encompasses buyers from the accessible luxury tier through the auction-house investment category. Most buyers shopping yellow cushion cut diamonds are targeting Fancy Yellow or Fancy Intense Yellow, the two most commercially available grades where 1ct cushion cuts start from [$1,549](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-26394333?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and the colour intensity is unmistakably visible in person and in photographs. The colour grading system, cut-shape interaction, and clarity trade-offs in yellow diamonds operate differently from the colourless diamond rules most buyers have learned before arriving at the fancy colour category.

GIA's Cushion Modified Brilliant cut notation on yellow diamond certificates is the dominant cut style in the fancy yellow market — not the standard Cushion Brilliant. The Modified Brilliant variant uses a slightly different facet arrangement that many cutters have found produces superior colour pooling in fancy colour stones, and the majority of Blue Nile's yellow cushion cut inventory carries the Cushion Modified Brilliant designation. Both cut styles produce excellent colour display in yellow diamonds; the Modified designation is not a quality downgrade.

## The Colour Cut Advantage

The Colour Cut Advantage is the mechanism by which the cushion cut concentrates and amplifies body colour more effectively than competing shapes at the same GIA colour grade. A round brilliant diamond's 57 triangular facets and steep crown angles direct light upward through a cone of highly reflective white-light return — which dilutes yellow body colour because the dominant visual impression is white brilliance rather than body saturation. A cushion modified brilliant cut uses larger, broader facet planes and a shallower crown angle that allows body colour to pool in the open table zone and read as a continuous field of saturated yellow rather than a divided, sparkle-fractured impression.

The practical implication is that a GIA Fancy Yellow cushion cut and a GIA Fancy Yellow round brilliant at the same colour grade will not look the same face-up. The cushion reads more saturated because its facet geometry pools colour in the table; the round reads more dispersed and lighter in colour intensity. Buyers moving from round to cushion for yellow diamonds often find they can target one grade lower on the GIA intensity scale and achieve equivalent or superior colour perception — a Fancy Yellow cushion routinely matching a Fancy Intense Yellow round at the same viewing distance.

For buyers comparing yellow cushion to yellow oval — the closest optical analogue — the cushion has the same large-table colour advantage over rounds, but with a more compact outline. The oval's elongated curved outline disperses colour slightly more than the cushion's flat-facet table at equivalent grades. For buyers whose primary goal is maximum colour saturation per dollar on a GIA-certified natural yellow diamond, the cushion modified brilliant is the optimal shape choice.

