## Yellow Cushion Cut Diamond Ring

The yellow cushion cut diamond ring requires a different metal strategy than a colourless cushion ring — yellow gold and rose gold amplify body colour, while white gold and platinum create a cool-metal contrast that can make the yellow appear isolated against the band. For Fancy Yellow and Fancy Intense Yellow grades, yellow gold is the dominant recommendation: the warm metal creates a visual continuum from band to stone, unifying the ring as a complete warm aesthetic rather than a coloured stone floating in a neutral mount. The [Petite Hidden Halo 14K Yellow Gold at $1,255](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-hidden-halo-solitaire-plus-engagement-ring-item-192506?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) (81 reviews) is the leading setting recommendation for 1–1.5ct yellow cushion cuts because the warm metal amplifies saturation and the hidden halo increases apparent size without competing with body colour.

Four-prong yellow gold solitaire settings allow maximum body colour visibility — no bezel coverage, no side-stone competition, the full open-table face-up area exposed — and for buyers who want the purest expression of The Colour Cut Advantage, yellow gold solitaire is the uncompromised configuration. The [Petite Solitaire 14K White Gold at $1,000](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194386?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) (1,020 reviews) works for buyers who want a bold colour-versus-metal contrast. Rose gold at [Petite Twist Diamond 14K Rose Gold $1,380](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-twist-diamond-engagement-ring-item-195538?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) (417 reviews) delivers warmth without the full yellow-on-yellow effect.

