## Yellow Cushion Cut vs Yellow Radiant

Yellow cushion cut versus yellow radiant cut is the primary shape comparison for buyers specifically targeting fancy yellow diamonds — and the decision is almost entirely about optical character rather than price, since both shapes deliver large-table colour efficiency well above round brilliant at comparable per-carat prices. The fundamental difference is facet geometry: the cushion modified brilliant uses broad, shallow facets that pool body colour in the open table; the radiant uses a more complex modified brilliant with triangular facets that break colour into a flashier, more fragmented return pattern. Buyers who want colour to read as a continuous, saturated field should prefer cushion; buyers who want colour integrated into a more sparkle-dominant visual impression should prefer radiant.

The yellow radiant cut's rectangular or square outline (typically L/W 1.00–1.30) has a more angular, geometric face-up presence than the cushion's soft-corner pillow outline. In engagement ring settings, the radiant's sharp corners add a modern, architectural quality; the cushion's rounded corners add a vintage, romantic quality. Neither is optically superior for yellow colour — both are strong colour-trapping shapes compared to round brilliant — but the cushion's advantage over radiant in colour concentration is smaller than the cushion's advantage over round, because the radiant is also a large-table design.

