## Lab Grown Yellow Cushion Cut Diamond

Lab grown yellow cushion cut diamonds exist and are available, but the market operates very differently from the colourless lab grown cushion market. The dominant production method for colourless lab grown diamonds (CVD) produces near-colourless or colourless stones by design; creating fancy yellow colour in a CVD stone requires specific nitrogen-incorporation control that is less common in CVD production. HPHT (high pressure, high temperature) lab grown diamonds more naturally produce yellow colour through nitrogen presence during crystal growth, and HPHT lab yellow cushion cuts are available from select vendors — but primary certified inventory at Blue Nile is predominantly natural GIA-certified stones.

Lab grown fancy yellow cushion cuts typically offer a per-carat discount of 50–70% relative to natural Fancy Yellow of equivalent grade and size when found in retail inventory. At Fancy Yellow grades where natural stones start from [$1,549 for 1ct](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-26394333?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), the absolute dollar saving from lab grown is smaller than the saving at D-VS colourless grades — because the natural Fancy Yellow base price is already relatively moderate compared to D-VS colourless diamonds. At Fancy Intense Yellow grades where natural starts from [$2,128 for 1ct](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-29114365?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), lab grown equivalents represent a more meaningful saving for buyers whose priority is saturation depth rather than natural origin.

Searching directly at Blue Nile's lab grown coloured diamond section is the most reliable approach since lab grown yellow cushion inventory changes frequently and availability varies significantly by grade and size. For the complete colourless lab grown cushion cut category covering IGI certification and pricing, see [Lab Grown Cushion Cut Diamond](/lab-grown-cushion-cut-diamond).

> **Farzana Hassan, GIA Graduate Gemologist:** "Lab grown yellow cushion cuts are an emerging category, not an established market. Buyers expecting the same 80–90% discount they see on colourless lab grown will be surprised — at Fancy Yellow grades, natural yellow cushion pricing is already accessible at $1,549, and lab grown yellow equivalents in GIA or IGI certified form are genuinely rare in retail inventory. I recommend natural GIA-certified Fancy Yellow cushion cuts for buyers who want a reliable, documented yellow diamond without the scarcity of searching for lab grown yellow."

## GIA Certification for Yellow Cushion Cut Diamonds

Every yellow cushion cut diamond in the Blue Nile inventory referenced in this guide carries a GIA certificate — the only external document that reliably grades fancy colour diamonds. GIA's fancy colour grading system is more complex than the D–Z colourless scale: GIA grades colour in terms of hue, tone, and saturation simultaneously, and the resulting grade describes both the colour's identity (yellow, orangy yellow, greenish yellow) and its intensity (Fancy Light, Fancy, Fancy Intense, Fancy Deep, Fancy Vivid). For yellow cushion cut buyers, the colour grade on the GIA certificate is the single most important quality descriptor — more important than clarity, more important than the cut style notation.

GIA does not issue a traditional cut grade for fancy colour diamonds the way it does for colourless round brilliants. The GIA certificate for a yellow cushion cut will show "Cushion Modified Brilliant" or "Cushion Cut" in the Shape and Cutting Style field, but will not show Excellent/Very Good/Good cut grades. Buyers accustomed to filtering by cut grade for colourless diamonds must adjust their evaluation criteria: for yellow cushion cuts, reviewing the stone's actual certificate photograph to assess how its facet structure reveals colour in the face-up position is the substitute for cut grade filtering.

GIA fluorescence on yellow cushion cut diamonds is described as None, Faint, Medium, or Strong Yellow — and unlike the complex fluorescence debate in colourless diamonds, yellow fluorescence in a yellow diamond typically enhances colour appearance under UV-rich lighting conditions. A yellow cushion cut with Strong Yellow fluorescence will appear more intensely yellow under daylight or fluorescent office light than the same stone under incandescent. Buyers should note the fluorescence on the GIA certificate and consider whether the primary wearing environments favour fluorescence enhancement.

## Expert Summary

The yellow cushion cut diamond is the most optically efficient shape for displaying natural fancy yellow colour — The Colour Cut Advantage is the structural reason why the cushion cut dominates the natural yellow diamond market at every carat tier from 1ct to 5ct+. The cushion's large, open-table facets pool body colour in the face-up zone in a way that makes Fancy Yellow read as Fancy Intense in side-by-side comparison with round brilliants, ovals, and marquise cuts at the same GIA grade. For buyers whose primary goal is maximum visible yellow saturation per dollar on a GIA-certified natural diamond, the cushion modified brilliant is the correct starting shape.

The Intensity Staircase is the planning framework every yellow cushion cut buyer needs before setting a budget. Fancy Yellow at 1ct starts from [$1,549](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-26394333?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — a price range that makes GIA-certified fancy colour accessible to buyers who previously assumed yellow diamonds were exclusively high-budget purchases. Fancy Intense Yellow at 1ct starts from [$2,128](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-29114365?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) and scales to [$3,280](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-27892009?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at VS2 — a premium only justified when deeper saturation is a non-negotiable priority over carat size.

> **Farzana Hassan, GIA Graduate Gemologist:** "The most common mistake I see yellow cushion cut diamond buyers make is treating clarity the same as colourless diamond clarity rules — spending to VS2 or VVS on a fancy yellow stone when the money would be far better spent on a higher colour intensity grade or a larger carat weight. At Fancy Yellow and Fancy Intense grades in a cushion cut, colour is the product. Eye-clean SI2 in a well-cut cushion modified brilliant will look identical to VS2 face-up; the colour intensity difference between Fancy Yellow and Fancy Intense Yellow at the same clarity will not."

## Final Verdict

**Best for buyers wanting maximum colour at the lowest entry price:** [GIA 1.01ct Fancy Yellow SI2 Cushion Modified at $1,549](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-26394333?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + [Hidden Halo 14K Yellow Gold at $1,255](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-hidden-halo-solitaire-plus-engagement-ring-item-192506?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) = **$2,804 complete yellow cushion halo ring.** GIA-certified natural fancy yellow, yellow gold amplifies colour, accessible budget for a fancy colour diamond ring.

**Best for buyers who want deeper saturation (Fancy Intense Yellow):** [GIA 1.01ct Fancy Intense Yellow SI2 at $2,128](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-29114365?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + [Petite Solitaire WG at $1,000](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194386?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) = **$3,128.** Fancy Intense delivers visibly richer saturation; white gold setting creates a bold colour-versus-metal contrast.

**Best for buyers prioritising carat weight in Fancy Yellow:** [GIA 2.01ct Fancy Yellow SI2 at $3,636](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-28980659?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) + [Petite Solitaire WG at $1,000](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194386?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) = **$4,636.** A 2ct GIA Fancy Yellow cushion at SI2 delivers substantially more face-up presence than a 1ct Fancy Intense Yellow at the same total budget — the correct trade-off for buyers who value size over saturation grade.

**Best for buyers at the 3ct+ collector tier:** [GIA 3.01ct Fancy Yellow VS1 at $15,655](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-29208718?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — the large-stone sweet spot where carat weight, clarity, and Fancy Yellow grade converge in a GIA-documented natural stone with genuine long-term value. Set in [Classic Four Prong Platinum at $1,180](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/classic-four-prong-solitaire-engagement-ring-item-194156?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for a bold cool-contrast statement; in [Hidden Halo YG at $1,255](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-hidden-halo-solitaire-plus-engagement-ring-item-192506?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for maximum warm-tone amplification.

## Frequently Asked Questions

**What is a yellow cushion cut diamond?**
A yellow cushion cut diamond is a cushion-shaped diamond graded by GIA as Fancy Light Yellow, Fancy Yellow, Fancy Intense Yellow, Fancy Deep Yellow, or Fancy Vivid Yellow. The cushion cut is the dominant shape in the natural yellow diamond market because its large, broad facets pool body colour in the face-up zone more effectively than round brilliant or oval shapes at equivalent GIA grades.

**How much does a 1ct yellow cushion cut diamond cost?**
A 1ct GIA Fancy Yellow cushion cut starts at [$1,549](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-26394333?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at SI2 and [$1,553](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-28516421?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) at VS2 — the clarity difference has almost no effect on price at this grade. Fancy Intense Yellow at 1ct starts at [$2,128](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-29114365?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for SI2 and [$3,280](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-27892009?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for VS2.

**What is Fancy Yellow vs Fancy Intense Yellow?**
Fancy Yellow is GIA's grade for medium yellow colour saturation — unmistakably yellow body colour visible in all lighting conditions. Fancy Intense Yellow is the next step up: deeper, more concentrated saturation with a richer, more electrifying yellow that reads immediately. The price difference at 1ct SI2 is approximately 37% — [$1,549 Fancy Yellow](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-26394333?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) vs [$2,128 Fancy Intense](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-29114365?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) — and The Intensity Staircase describes how this gap widens non-linearly as you move toward Fancy Vivid Yellow.

**Why do buyers choose cushion cut for yellow diamonds?**
The cushion cut's open table and large, shallow facet planes pool body colour in the face-up zone rather than breaking it into sparkle fragments — this is The Colour Cut Advantage. A Fancy Yellow cushion reads more saturated than a Fancy Yellow round brilliant at the same GIA grade because the cushion's facet geometry works with body colour instead of competing with white-light return. Most experienced fancy yellow buyers prioritise cushion over round for this reason.

**Is a yellow cushion cut diamond GIA certified?**
Yes — every yellow cushion cut diamond in the Blue Nile inventory referenced in this guide carries a GIA certificate. GIA is the gold standard for fancy colour diamond grading because its colour grading methodology — assessing hue, tone, and saturation simultaneously — is more rigorous and consistent than other laboratories. Never buy a natural fancy yellow diamond without a GIA certificate.

**What clarity should I choose for a yellow cushion cut diamond?**
SI2 is the correct clarity anchor for most yellow cushion buyers at 1–2ct. The priority in fancy yellow diamonds is colour intensity and carat weight — at SI2 with no eye-visible inclusions in the face-up table, the stone is indistinguishable from VS2 at the same colour grade in person. Redirect clarity budget toward colour intensity grade or carat weight instead.

**Should I use yellow gold or white gold for a yellow cushion cut ring?**
Yellow gold amplifies and warms the yellow body colour, creating a unified warm aesthetic — the dominant choice for buyers who want maximum colour saturation appearance. White gold creates a bold contrast — yellow stone against a bright, cool band — which some buyers prefer for its graphic quality. Rose gold is a warm middle ground that flatters yellow diamonds without full yellow-on-yellow saturation.

**What metal is best for a yellow cushion cut engagement ring?**
14K yellow gold is the top recommendation because the warm metal amplifies body colour and 14K alloy is more durable than 18K for daily wear. The [Petite Hidden Halo 14K Yellow Gold at $1,255](https://www.bluenile.com/engagement-rings/design-your-own-ring/petite-hidden-halo-solitaire-plus-engagement-ring-item-192506?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) is the leading setting for yellow cushion cuts at 1–1.5ct.

**What is a light yellow cushion cut diamond?**
A light yellow cushion cut diamond is typically a stone graded Near Colourless (H–J on D–Z colourless scale) or Faint Yellow (K–M) rather than a GIA fancy colour grade. These stones carry colourless diamond pricing with some yellow warmth and do not carry a fancy colour premium. For buyers who specifically want visible yellow colour, a GIA Fancy Yellow certified cushion cut delivers a documented colour grade and more reliable long-term value context.

**What is a natural fancy yellow cushion diamond?**
A natural fancy yellow cushion diamond is a mined (not lab grown) cushion-shaped diamond graded by GIA as Fancy Yellow or higher intensity. The "natural" designation distinguishes from lab grown yellow diamonds, which can be produced with similar colour grades through HPHT processes. Natural fancy yellow diamonds carry a provenance premium over lab grown equivalents, and GIA grading confirms both the natural origin and the colour grade simultaneously.

**How much does a 2ct yellow cushion cut diamond cost?**
A 2ct GIA Fancy Yellow SI2 cushion cut starts at [$3,636](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-28980659?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). The same grade at SI1 is [$4,539](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-29452360?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), at VS2 is [$5,674](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-28765319?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational), and at VVS1 is [$6,703](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-20807941?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational). A 2ct Fancy Intense Yellow SI2 is [$7,052](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-22116638?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational).

**What is the cheapest yellow cushion cut diamond at Blue Nile?**
The cheapest GIA-certified yellow cushion cut at Blue Nile starts at [$1,549](https://www.bluenile.com/colored-diamond-details/yellow-26394333?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational) for a 1.01ct Fancy Yellow SI2 cushion modified brilliant. This is the Fancy Yellow grade entry point — a fully GIA-certified natural fancy colour diamond with visible yellow saturation and an eye-clean appearance at SI2 clarity.

**How does a yellow cushion cut compare to a yellow radiant cut?**
Yellow cushion versus yellow radiant is a close comparison because both are large-table shapes that concentrate body colour well. The cushion's pooled-colour facet pattern creates a more continuous saturated impression; the radiant's triangular facets create more fragmentation and sparkle alongside the colour. The cushion reads as slightly more saturated at equivalent GIA grade; the radiant reads as more sparkle-dominant. Both operate at comparable per-carat prices at equivalent GIA grades.

**Is a yellow cushion cut diamond a good investment?**
Natural GIA-certified fancy yellow cushion cuts at Fancy Yellow and above have demonstrated stable long-term value because their supply is geologically constrained — yellow colour in natural diamonds requires specific nitrogen conditions during formation. Fancy Intense Yellow and Fancy Vivid Yellow stones at 3ct+ in cushion form are genuine collector assets with auction records. Fancy Yellow at 1ct is accessible luxury rather than a pure investment vehicle — its value lies primarily in the quality of the ring it creates.

